The Limit of Panic
Copenhagen — We often hear, and we know, that the world as we know it will meet its end, and the usual explanation is ecological collapse.
In fact, since the Club of Rome published "The Limits to Growth," the seminal work that marked the beginning of the apocalypse-themed warnings, its core ideas have accompanied us ever since.
But time is not forgiving.
The 1972 book "The Limits to Growth" warned humanity that a catastrophic collapse was imminent.
However, afterward we saw financial panic, but no real shortages or production collapses.
In contrast, the resources created by human genius are more than sufficient to meet human consumption needs.
But the basic idea of "The Limits to Growth" still holds: we continue a trend of being preoccupied with misleading solutions to minor issues, while ignoring the big problems and wise solutions.
In the early 1970s, the optimism about technology faded, the Vietnam War turned into a disaster, society fell into turmoil, and the economy stagnated.
Rachel Carson's 1962 book "Silent Spring" sparked public fear of pollution and ignited the modern environmentalist movement; Paul Ehrlich's 1968 book "The Population Bomb" made everything clear.
On the first Earth Day in 1970, people were deeply pessimistic.
The intent of "The Limits to Growth" is to make people worry about resource depletion.
This is our fate, because too many people consume too much.
Even if our genius buys us some time, we will eventually destroy the Earth and ourselves through pollution.
The only hope is to stagnate economic growth, reduce consumption, promote recycling, and force people to have fewer children, thereby achieving social stability at a level of poverty significantly worse than today's.
This view continues to resonate to this day, despite being completely wrong.
For example, the authors of "The Limits to Growth" predicted that the world would run out of aluminum, copper, gold, lead, mercury, molybdenum, natural gas, oil, silver, tin, tungsten, and zinc before 2013.
However, although the prices of goods have recently rebounded somewhat, overall they have fallen to one-third of the levels seen 150 years ago.
Technological innovation replaced mercury in batteries, dentistry materials, and thermometers, leading to an 98% decline in mercury consumption by the year 2000 and a 90% drop in its price.
More broadly, since 1946, the supply of copper, aluminum, iron, and zinc has exceeded demand, thanks to the discovery of new reserves and more economical new extraction technologies.
Similarly, oil and natural gas were originally expected to be exhausted by 1990 and 1992 respectively; today, their reserves are higher than the 1970 level, despite a significant increase in our consumption.
In the past six years, shale gas alone has doubled the potential natural gas reserves in the United States and cut prices in half.
As for economic collapse, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change estimates that global per capita GDP will increase 14 times this century, with developing countries seeing an increase of 24 times.
"The Limits to Growth" was wrong because the authors overlooked the greatest resource: our own ingenuity.
Population growth began to slow down since the 1960s.
The food supply has not collapsed (1.5 billion hectares of arable land are being utilized, in addition to 2.7 billion hectares of reserve land).
The rate of malnutrition has been reduced by more than half, dropping from 35% of the world's population to 16%.
Pollution hasn't bothered us.
The Club of Rome imagines a pastoral past where there was no air pollution from suspended particles, and everyone was happy farmers, while in the future, heating chimneys will make it impossible for us to breathe. Reality is entirely the opposite.
In 1900, the global population was only 1.5 billion, yet nearly 3 million people—equivalent to one person in every 500—died each year from air pollution, most of which was indoor air pollution.
Now, the rate has dropped to one death in every 2,000 people.
Although the number of deaths caused by pollution is still higher than that from malaria, the mortality rate is declining rather than increasing.
Despite this, the ideas promoted by "The Limits to Growth" continue to influence the thinking of the public and elites.
Take recycling, for example; it's usually just a gesture to make people feel better, costing a lot to the environment but yielding little in return.
For example, paper is usually sourced from sustainable forests rather than tropical rainforests.
What results from procedures related to paper recycling and government subsidies is low-quality paper, which actually protects resources that are not under threat.
Similarly, concerns about overpopulation led to self-destructive policies, such as China's one-child policy and India's forced sterilization.
In addition, although pesticides and other pollutants are believed to kill half of humanity, effective pesticide regulation has resulted in only 20 annual deaths in the United States, while the use of pesticides has created more affordable and abundant food supplies.
In fact, relying solely on organic agriculture — a movement driven by pesticide panic — would impose an additional $100 billion annual cost on the United States.
Agricultural efficiency will decrease by 16 percent, and to maintain current output, 65 million hectares of farmland—half the size of modern-day California—will need to be cultivated.
Rising prices will lead to a decline in the consumption of fruits and vegetables, resulting in serious negative health impacts (including an increase of tens of thousands of cancer-related deaths annually).
Being immersed in dark scenarios prevents us from focusing on the real global threats.
Poverty is one of the biggest killers, yet easily curable diseases still cause the death of 15 million people each year — equivalent to a quarter of the total number of deaths.
The solution lies in economic growth.
After people escape poverty, most of them can afford the cost of preventing infectious diseases.
Over the past three decades, China has lifted 680 million people out of poverty, leading the world in reducing the global poverty population by nearly one billion.
This led to widespread improvements in hygiene, lifespan, and quality of life.
Four decades since the publication of "The Limits to Growth" have shown that we need more, not less, growth.
The expansion of trade is estimated to generate over 100 trillion dollars in benefits annually by the end of this century, far surpassing the "comfortable" policies of hesitation and fear instilled by the spread of fear.
But this requires us to abandon the anti-growth mindset and use our boundless potential to create a brighter future.
